#speculation(title: [Inadequate Harm Monitoring in Psychosocial ME/CFS Trials Constitutes Systematic Evidence Blindness])[
Schomerus et al.\ (2026, p.\ 5–6) highlight a critical asymmetry: drug trials routinely monitor and report adverse events as a regulatory requirement, but psychosocial intervention trials for ME/CFS—despite evidence that activation-based approaches cause harm in a substantial minority of patients—operate under far laxer standards. A systematic review of psychotherapy studies for LC found that 8 of 11 included studies provided no information on adverse effects whatsoever @Schomerus2026PsycheRole. PEM, the decisive clinical parameter for safety, is frequently not assessed or not assessed differentially as an adverse outcome. Many psychosocial trials lack control groups, making it impossible to distinguish therapeutic effects from spontaneous recovery or non-specific expectation effects.

_(Certainty: 0.65. The specific claim about 8/11 psychotherapy studies lacking adverse effect data is reported by Schomerus et al. but the underlying reference could not be located—this is a secondary citation. The general pattern of inadequate harm monitoring in GET/CBT trials is independently documented by Kindlon (2011, @Kindlon2011GET) and by the systematic review evidence of Cooper et al. (2025, @Cooper2025PacingVsGET) showing superior safety for pacing vs GET. The broader asymmetry between drug and psychosocial trial safety standards is well-recognized in clinical trial methodology. Falsifiability: directly testable—a systematic review of adverse event reporting in all published ME/CFS psychosocial intervention trials would confirm or refute the 8/11 claim and establish the rate of adequate safety monitoring. Origin: literature — derived from Schomerus 2026's argument, with supporting evidence from Cooper 2025.)_
] <spec:harm-monitoring-gap>
